{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2094"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2094"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.09,0.06,0.75,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2094"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63551"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4112"},{"type":"tags","id":"4137"},{"type":"tags","id":"4141"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for assessment of increasingly frequent urinary incontinence. She has advanced Alzheimer\u0027s dementia and resides in a High Level Care Nursing Home. She has osteoarthritis and hypertension. Her medications include paracetamol and perindopril. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals a grade 2 cystocele with associated vaginal wall prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systemic oestrogen therapy","Pelvic floor exercises","Vaginal oestrogen cream","Pessary ring","Surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with pelvic organ prolapse (POP) in the context of advanced age and significant cognitive impairment. The management approach must consider both the effectiveness of treatment and the patient\u0027s ability to participate in care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPessary ring\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option as it provides mechanical support to the prolapsed organs without requiring surgery or active patient participation. It is particularly suitable for elderly patients who are poor surgical candidates or those with cognitive impairment. Regular checks every 3-6 months are required to prevent complications. Informed consent would be needed for its insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic floor exercises\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective in this case as the patient\u0027s cognitive impairment would prevent her from learning and consistently performing the exercises correctly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaginal oestrogen cream\u003C/strong\u003E, while useful for vulvovaginal atrophy symptoms, has limited effectiveness for established POP. It may be used as an adjunct to pessary treatment to prevent vaginal erosions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic oestrogen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this patient due to her advanced age, as initiating treatment over 60 years carries increased cardiovascular and other risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s advanced age and dementia, which increase both operative risk and the likelihood of post-operative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPOP is common in elderly women and is often associated with urinary symptoms. The choice of management should be individualised based on severity of symptoms, patient factors, and ability to comply with treatment. Conservative management is preferred in patients with significant comorbidities or cognitive impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pessary ring is appropriate first-line management for pelvic organ prolapse in elderly patients who are poor surgical candidates","Conservative management of pelvic organ prolapse is preferred when there is high surgical risk or likelihood of recurrence","Regular pessary checks every 3-6 months are essential to prevent complications"],"references":["Chung S-H, Kim WB. Various Approaches and Treatments for Pelvic Organ Prolapse in Women. J Menopausal Med. 2018;24(3):155-62. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6336571/","Persu C, Chapple CR, Cauni V, Gutue S, Geavlete P. Pelvic Organ Prolapse Quantification System (POP-Q) - a new era in pelvic prolapse staging. J Med Life. 2011 Jan-Mar;4(1):75-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21505577/","Systemic Menopausal Hormonal Therapy. In: eTG complete [online]. [Updated 2020 Dec; cited 2023 March 30]. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/","Intravaginal Therapy for Menopausal Symptoms. In: eTG complete [online]. [Updated 2020 Dec; cited 2023 March 30]. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2094"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":